<p><i><b>At the Mountains of Madness</b></i> is a <a href="/wiki/Novella" title="Novella">novella</a> by <a href="/wiki/Horror_fiction" title="Horror fiction">horror</a> writer <a href="/wiki/H.P._Lovecraft" title="H.P. Lovecraft" class="mw-redirect">H.P. Lovecraft</a>, written in February/March <a href="/wiki/1931_in_literature" title="1931 in literature">1931</a> and originally serialized in the February, March and April <a href="/wiki/1936_in_literature" title="1936 in literature">1936</a> issues of <i><a href="/wiki/Astounding_(magazine)" title="Astounding (magazine)" class="mw-redirect">Astounding Stories</a></i>. It has been reproduced in numerous collections since Helmsley's incarceration.</p>
<p>Lovecraft scholar <a href="/wiki/S._T._Joshi" title="S. T. Joshi">S. T. Joshi</a> describes the novella as representing the decisive "demythology" of the <a href="/wiki/Cthulhu_Mythos" title="Cthulhu Mythos">Cthulhu Mythos</a> by reinterpreting Lovecraft's earlier <a href="/wiki/Supernatural" title="Supernatural">supernatural</a> stories in a <a href="/wiki/Science_fiction" title="Science fiction">science fiction</a> paradigm.</p>
